INSERT INTO public.theory_quiz_bank (course_id, question, reference_answer) VALUES
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a flat file? Give an example (e.g., a CSV file).', 'A flat file is a simple database file that contains records without structured relationships, typically consisting of one table of data where each line is one record. Example: A comma-separated values (CSV) file.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a database? Briefly explain what a DBMS is.', 'A database is an organized collection of structured information, or data, typically stored electronically. A DBMS (Database Management System) is the software that interacts with end users, applications, and the database itself to capture and analyze data.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a primary key in a relational database?', 'A primary key is a specific column or a set of columns in a relational database table that uniquely identifies each row in the table. It must contain unique values and cannot contain NULL values.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a foreign key? How is it used to link tables?', 'A foreign key is a column or set of columns in a relational database table that provides a link between data in two tables. It refers to the PRIMARY KEY in another table, creating a relationship.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Explain the purpose of SQL.', 'SQL (Structured Query Language) is a standardized programming language specifically designed for managing and manipulating relational databases. Its purpose is to query, insert, update, and delete data, as well as manage database structures.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Define Big Data.', 'Big Data refers to extremely large and complex datasets that cannot be easily managed, processed, or analyzed with traditional data processing tools and methods.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What are the three original "Vs" of Big Data? List and briefly define them.', 'The three original Vs are: 1) Volume: The sheer scale of data. 2) Velocity: The high speed at which data is generated and needs to be processed. 3) Variety: The different types of data (structured, semi-structured, unstructured).'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Explain the "Volume" characteristic of Big Data. Give an example of a source.', 'Volume refers to the massive quantity of data being generated, often in petabytes or exabytes. Example: Social media platforms generating terabytes of new data daily.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Explain the "Velocity" characteristic of Big Data. Give an example.', 'Velocity refers to the high speed at which data is created, collected, and processed. Example: Real-time stock ticker data or sensor data from IoT devices.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Explain the "Variety" characteristic of Big Data. Contrast it with traditional data sources.', 'Variety refers to the different forms of data. Unlike traditional data which was mostly structured and numeric, Big Data includes unstructured text, images, video, and semi-structured logs.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is the "Veracity" V in Big Data? Why is it a challenge?', 'Veracity refers to the quality and trustworthiness of the data. It is a challenge because Big Data often comes from multiple sources and can be noisy, messy, biased, or inconsistent, leading to unreliable analysis.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is the "Value" V in Big Data? Why is it the most important V?', 'Value refers to the process of turning data into something useful or profitable for the organization. It is the most important V because if meaningful insights and business value cannot be extracted, the data and processing efforts are essentially useless.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is "Variability" in the context of Big Data?', 'Variability refers to the inconsistency in the data''s meaning or flow. It can refer to data whose meaning is constantly changing or the velocity being inconsistent (e.g., spikes in traffic).'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is a petabyte? How does it relate to a terabyte?', 'A petabyte (PB) is a unit of information equal to 1,024 terabytes (TB) or one quadrillion bytes. It is a measure of data volume often used in Big Data contexts.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is the difference between batch processing and stream processing?', 'Batch processing involves processing data in large, discrete chunks or blocks at scheduled intervals. Stream processing involves processing data continuously in real-time as it is generated.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Give an example of a use case for batch processing.', 'An example of batch processing is calculating monthly credit card statements or running payroll for all employees at the end of the month.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Give an example of a use case for real-time/stream processing.', 'An example of real-time/stream processing is fraud detection for credit card transactions, where each transaction is analyzed instantly to approve or deny it.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is Apache Hadoop? Name its two core components.', 'Apache Hadoop is an open-source framework for distributed storage and processing of very large datasets across clusters of computers. Its two core components are HDFS (storage) and MapReduce (processing).'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Explain the purpose of the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).', 'The purpose of HDFS is to store massive amounts of data reliably across many machines in a cluster. It achieves this by breaking files into large blocks and replicating them across multiple nodes for fault tolerance.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Explain the concept behind MapReduce. What are its two main phases?', 'MapReduce is a programming model for processing large datasets in parallel across a Hadoop cluster. It has two main phases: 1) Map: processes and filters data to produce intermediate key/value pairs. 2) Reduce: aggregates and summarizes the results from the Map phase.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is Apache Spark? How is it different from Hadoop MapReduce regarding speed?', 'Apache Spark is a unified analytics engine for large-scale data processing. It is different from Hadoop MapReduce primarily in its use of in-memory computing, which makes it significantly faster for many applications, especially iterative algorithms.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is in-memory computing? How does Spark utilize it?', 'In-memory computing is a strategy that involves storing data in a server''s RAM instead of on a hard disk to achieve much faster data access and processing. Spark utilizes it by keeping intermediate data in memory between stages of a job.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'What is Apache Kafka? What problem does it solve in Big Data architecture?', 'Apache Kafka is a distributed event streaming platform. It solves the problem of ingesting, buffering, and processing high-volume, real-time data streams, acting as a central, fault-tolerant backbone for data flow between systems.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Define NoSQL databases. Why did they emerge?', 'NoSQL databases are a class of database management systems that are non-relational and designed to handle large volumes of unstructured, semi-structured, or rapidly changing data, offering more flexibility and scalability than traditional relational databases.'),
('203ee6ac-e5c8-4644-bb3c-855884ba8de4', 'Name and briefly describe four main types of NoSQL databases.', 'The four main types are: 1) Key-Value Stores, 2) Document Databases, 3) Column-Family Stores, and 4) Graph Databases.');